# Repo Atlas — <repository name>

> **Built at:** commit `<SHA>` (<YYYY-MM-DD>) • **Refreshed:** <YYYY-MM-DD or "never">
> **Staleness check:** `git diff --stat <SHA>..HEAD` — small drift: trust the atlas and deep-read
> only the drifted areas; structural drift (new/moved top-level modules, manifest changes):
> refresh via `/atlas` before relying on it.

The repo-level MAX artifact: one deep read of the codebase, amortized across every subsequent
work item. MAX actions (`/design`, `/plan` cold starts, `/refactor` analysis, `/impact`) consume
this **first** and deep-read only what has drifted since `<SHA>` — instead of re-reading the
repo from scratch per work item.

**Author discipline (non-negotiable):**

- **Bounded.** Target ≤ ~300 lines. Reference `file:line`; never inline code or whole docs.
- **Descriptive, not aspirational.** The atlas records how the repo *is*, including the warts —
  an atlas that describes the intended architecture misleads every consumer.
- **Stable ordering.** Refreshes update sections in place; consumers cache-read this file.

